% ====================================================================
% test_gc_local_packed_global_ref.trx -- Phase C regression
% ====================================================================
% Phase C of plan_gc_walks_local_containers.md (shipped 2026-05-09).
% A top-level proc defined outside any `${...}` block lands in local
% VM (its Packed body is vm_alloc'd, sub-m_vm_global).  An inner
% `${ ... }` nested inside that body allocates ITS body proc -- AND
% any literals scanned within -- in GLOBAL VM, because
% scan_global_block toggles m_curr_alloc_global=true during the inner
% scan.  The reference chain is therefore:
%
%     dict-root -> /local-proc (LOCAL Packed)
%                       -> ${ [ ... ] } body literal (GLOBAL Packed)
%                              -> [ ... ] Array literal (GLOBAL Array)
%
% Pre-Phase-C, gc_mark_object silent-skipped local Packeds (Phases A
% + B walked Dict/Set/Tagged/Array/Record but not Packed), so GC
% sweeps the global body-proc + Array on its first pass.  When the
% local proc next runs, the Packed decoder reads the freed bytes;
% if the allocator has reused the slot the bytes are scratch -- a 0 byte
% in the stream decodes as common-op index 0 (`Exch`), which then
% trips opstack-underflow as the canonical symptom.
%
% Phase C walks local Packeds via extract_next_packed (the same
% decoder global Packeds use), recursing gc_mark_object on each
% literal.  The visited-offset set (shared with Phases A+B) breaks
% cycles -- local blocks have no GvmBlock header so the per-block
% m_mark_gen short-circuit doesn't apply.
%
% This file is isolated from test_gc_local_dict_global_ref.trx so the
% heap state at GC time is clean -- the bug requires the freed
% global-VM body-proc block to be reissued before the next decode,
% and earlier sections' allocations can otherwise displace the
% reuse to a different slot.
% ====================================================================

% rt-ok counts failures in a restore-immune slot -- string byte writes
% are unjournaled, so the count survives assertions made inside save
% scopes, and the 1-byte string lives in LOCAL VM, invisible to the
% global-heap/gc-counter probes some files assert on.  The file THROWS
% at EOF: test_all counts a file as failed only when its run throws,
% so print-only failures would slip the suite verdict.
/rt-fails 1 string def
rt-fails 0 16#0#b put
/rt-ok { exch { = } { (FAILED: ) print = rt-fails 0  rt-fails 0 get /integer-type cast 1 add dup 255 gt { pop 255 } if /byte-type cast  put } if-else } def

% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% Force any freed global blocks to be reissued so a stale offset
% reads scratch values, not coincidentally-intact bytes.  Match the
% shape of the inner ${ [...] } body proc closely: small Packed
% bodies + 10-element Arrays.  Each iteration allocates and drops
% several global composites of varying sizes so the allocator's free
% list services the inner-${} block whatever its exact size class.
% --------------------------------------------------------------------
/force-reuse-mixed {
    0 1 19 {
        pop
        ${ [ 9001 9002 9003 9004 9005 9006 9007 9008 9009 9010 ] } pop
        ${ [ 7001 7002 7003 7004 7005 ] } pop
        ${ [ 8001 8002 8003 ] } pop
    } for
} def

% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% SECTION 1: local Packed proc with inner ${...} body proc literal
% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% /inner-loop is defined at top-level (m_curr_alloc_global=false at
% scan time) so its Packed body is in LOCAL VM.  The for-body
% contains `${ [ 901..910 ] }` -- scan_global_block toggles
% m_curr_alloc_global=true during the inner scan, so:
%   - the inner ${...}'s body proc is a Packed in GLOBAL VM
%   - the [ 901..910 ] literal Array is in GLOBAL VM
% The inner body proc Object literal is encoded inside /inner-loop's
% LOCAL Packed bytes -- the only path to mark it from the dict root
% is to decode local Packed bodies, which is exactly what Phase C
% adds.

/inner-loop {
    0 1 5 {
        pop
        ${ [ 901 902 903 904 905 906 907 908 909 910 ] } pop
    } for
} def

% Warm-up call: no GC has fired yet, just confirm the proc runs.
inner-loop

% Outer ${...} containing an array-from-mark op (executable names
% inside [ ... ] force a runtime build instead of a scan-time
% literal).  Inside the body, vm-global-gc walks all roots; without
% Phase C the inner-${} body proc + [ 901..910 ] Array become
% unreachable and get swept.  The force-reuse-mixed step then
% over-writes the freed bytes.  Re-running inner-loop reads the
% reissued bytes; without Phase C the decoder dispatches `Exch`
% (or another corrupt token) and trips opstack-underflow.
${
    [
        201 202 203
        vm-global-gc pop
        force-reuse-mixed
        inner-loop
        301 302 303
    ]
    make-executable
}
exec

% Stack now has: 201 202 203 301 302 303 (top).
303 eq                                        (1: outer 303 intact) rt-ok
302 eq                                        (1: outer 302 intact) rt-ok
301 eq                                        (1: outer 301 intact) rt-ok
203 eq                                        (1: outer 203 intact) rt-ok
202 eq                                        (1: outer 202 intact) rt-ok
201 eq                                        (1: outer 201 intact) rt-ok

% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% SECTION 2: nested local Packeds (Packed -> Packed chain)
% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% /outer-proc is a local Packed whose body contains a literal local
% Packed (the inline {...} sub-proc) which in turn contains an inner
% ${...} body literal in global VM.  Phase C must descend through
% both local Packeds to reach the global body proc.

/outer-proc {
    {
        ${ [ 1001 1002 1003 1004 1005 ] } pop
    } exec
} def

outer-proc                                    % warm-up

${
    vm-global-gc pop
    force-reuse-mixed
    outer-proc
    42
}
exec
42 eq                                         (2: nested-local-Packed chain works) rt-ok

% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% SECTION 3: probe sees retained globals as live
% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% After everything, the probe should see at least the inner ${...}
% body procs we retain via /inner-loop and /outer-proc.  Two retained
% globals minimum (one body proc per def).

vm-global-gc-probe /probe-final exch def
probe-final /live get 2 ge                    (3: probe sees >= 2 live retained) rt-ok

rt-fails 0 get /integer-type cast 0 gt { /rt-assertions-failed throw } if
(test_gc_local_packed_global_ref: ALL TESTS PASSED) =
(__test_ok__) =
